an, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Renty","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Angel, Alicia, Bolivar, Francisco, Jorge, Juan, Julio, Magda, Manuel, Nydia, Virgen.","Spanish and Portuguese: most probably from <i>renta</i> ‘income’, ‘rental’. This name is common mainly in the Caribbean; it is rare in Spain."],"variants":[{"name":"Rentas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Pedro, Ramonita, Angel, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Tomas, Aida, Armando, Blanca.","Spanish and Portuguese: plural form of   Renta  ."]}]},{"name":"Allard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Andre, Emile, Normand, Marcel, Alain, Armand, Gaston, Pierre, Antoine, Benoit, Fernand.","English: from a Middle English personal name, <i>Alard</i>, <i>Adelard</i>, <i>Aylard</i>, or <i>Elard</i>. The former two names are usually of native English origin, from Old English <i>Æthelheard</i>, composed of the elements <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heard</i> ‘hard, bold’. Alternatively, the surname may be of continental origin, from an ancient Germanic name (see 2 below), which developed in Old French to <i>Alard</i>, and in Middle Dutch to <i>Adelaert</i> and <i>Alaert</i>. The continental names were used in post-Conquest England by Normans and Flemings. Later development of <i>-ard</i> to <i>-ett</i> and <i>-att</i> in surnames means that these personal names may also lie behind some examples of e.g. <b>Allatt</b> and   Hallett  .","French: from the medieval personal name <i>Alard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Adelhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy’. Compare   Allar  ,   Allor  ,   Allord  , and   Allore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellerd","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Allard  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain.","Probably an altered form of German Ellert, a variant of Ehlert."]},{"name":"Ellert","meanings":["Old German: Illustrious"]},{"name":"Allor","meanings":["Hebrew: An oak."]},{"name":"Hallett","meanings":["English (mainly Somerset and Dorset): variant of <b>Allatt</b>, itself a variant of   Allard  , with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Ellard","meanings":["English: variant of   Allard  ."]},{"name":"Allore","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Allard  ."]},{"name":"Allord","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Allard  ."]}]},{"name":"ou","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Wealthy’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alain","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Breton form of <i>Alan</i>, now common in all parts of France.  See  <b>Alan</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Baron Allard ou Alain de Renty was born in 1191, in Renty, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Arnould II De Renty, was 32 and his mother, Blanche de Berghes-st-Winnoc, was 20. He married Nicole de Neulles in 1225, in Neulles, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. He died in 1226, in his hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1191–1226":"1191–1226","1194–1246":"1194–1246","–1229":"–1229","1205–Female":"1205–Su